{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8c17df45-ebeb-4615-a9c2-549f1f73ba41","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, but I can tell you exactly what you need to configure to publish a C# MCP server as a `dotnet tool`:\n\n### In your `.csproj`, add these properties:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n  <PackageOutputPath>./nupkg</PackageOutputPath>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n**Key properties:**\n- **`PackAsTool`** — makes it installable via `dotnet tool install`\n- **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command users will run\n- **`OutputType`** must be `Exe` (should already be set for a stdio server)\n\n### Build, pack, and publish:\n\n```bash\ndotnet pack -c Release\ndotnet nuget push ./nupkg/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_NUGET_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install with:\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server   # runs via stdio\n```\n\nThat's the core setup. Need help scaffolding the actual project files?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"29d977ac-daa3-4d2e-b7f7-ecfa69c436c3","outputTokens":423,"requestId":"E046:16DC31:1137613:129BD38:69E74FCE"},"id":"bc92c2a1-2fb1-437d-b98e-8ba602d44275","timestamp":"2026-04-21T10:22:14.662Z","parentId":"11ec7853-177b-4104-9c9b-50e8db8fc066"}
